Project Overview: Mini Database (MASM + Irvine32)
Let‚Äôs assume your mini database stores student records (Name, ID, and Marks).
Main features:

Add new record

Display all records

Search by ID

Delete or update record

Save/load data from file

üë©‚Äçüíª Division of Tasks Between Aleeza and Rehma
üß† Aleeza ‚Äî Core Logic + Data Management
Main focus: database structure, logic, and record manipulation
You‚Äôll handle most of the computational logic and data structures.

Your tasks:

Design and declare data structures:

Arrays for IDs, names, marks

Example:

ids DWORD 10 DUP(?)
names BYTE 10 DUP(20 DUP(?))
marks DWORD 10 DUP(?)
count DWORD 0
(Show use of arrays and memory management)

Add Record Procedure:

Input name, ID, and marks using ReadString, ReadInt

Store in the arrays

Increment count

Use string operations to save name

Search Record Procedure:

Input ID ‚Üí linear search through ids

Display corresponding name and marks

Uses loops, CMP, conditional jumps

Delete or Update Record Procedure (optional bonus):

Reuse your search logic

If found, either overwrite data or shift array elements up

Great chance to use looping + conditional branching

Testing and Integration:

Combine your procedures into a proper main menu call structure.

Assembly concepts you‚Äôll cover:

Arrays and indexing

Conditional branching (JE, JNE, etc.)

Loops

Procedures with parameters

String operations

Data validation logic

üë©‚Äçüíª Rehma ‚Äî User Interface + File Handling + Utilities
Main focus: input/output interface, saving and loading records, menu system

Her tasks:

Menu Display + Control:

Show main menu:

1. Add Record
2. Display All
3. Search
4. Save to File
5. Load from File
6. Exit
Read user choice using ReadInt

Use CMP + JE/JMP to call relevant procedures

(Nice use of branching and control flow)

Display All Records Procedure:

Loop through arrays and print each record

Use WriteString, WriteInt

Practice loops, procedure calls, and formatting

File Handling Procedures:

Use Irvine32‚Äôs file I/O routines:

CreateFile, OpenFile, WriteToFile, ReadFromFile, CloseFile

Implement SaveRecords and LoadRecords

You‚Äôll show advanced Assembly, demonstrating real data persistence.

Input/Output Helper Procedures:

Procedure for reading strings (e.g., names)

Procedure for displaying formatted record output (so Aleeza can reuse it)

UI Polish (Optional Bonus):

Add borders, text formatting, spacing

Maybe even ‚Äúclearing‚Äù screen using multiple CRLFs

Assembly concepts covered:

Loops and control flow

File I/O operations

String and integer input/output

Procedures and modular programming

System calls through Irvine routines

üîó How You‚Äôll Combine Work
Part	Person Responsible	How it Connects
Data declarations	Aleeza	Shared through .data section
Procedures	Both	Keep each in .code under labels (Aleeza_Proc / Rehma_Proc)
Menu control	Rehma	Calls Aleeza‚Äôs procedures
File save/load	Rehma	Reads/writes Aleeza‚Äôs arrays
Main loop	Rehma	Integrates all functionality
üß© Example Structure (Simplified)
.data
; Shared arrays
ids DWORD 10 DUP(?)
names BYTE 10 DUP(20 DUP(?))
marks DWORD 10 DUP(?)
count DWORD 0

.code
main PROC
    CALL ShowMenu
    exit
main ENDP

; ==== Rehma‚Äôs Side ====
ShowMenu PROC
    ; display menu, take choice
    ; call AddRecord / DisplayAll / etc.
ShowMenu ENDP

SaveToFile PROC
    ; file handling code
SaveToFile ENDP

; ==== Aleeza‚Äôs Side ====
AddRecord PROC
    ; input id, name, marks
AddRecord ENDP

SearchRecord PROC
    ; search logic
SearchRecord ENDP
END main
